context: One of the most prominent movies filmed in Alaska is MGM's Eskimo/Mala The Magnificent, starring Alaska Native <a0_0><b4_0>Ray Mala<b4_0/><a0_0/>. In 1932 an expedition set out from MGM's studios in Hollywood to Alaska to film what was then billed as "The Biggest Picture Ever Made." Upon arriving in Alaska, they set up <a1_0><b5_0>"Camp Hollywood"<b5_0/><a1_0/> in <a2_0><b6_0><b7_0>Northwest<b7_0/><b6_0/><a2_0/> Alaska, where they lived during the duration of the filming. Louis B. Mayer spared no expense in spite of the remote location, going so far as to hire the chef <a3_0><b8_0>from the Hotel Roosevelt in Hollywood<b8_0/><a3_0/> to prepare meals.
